    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "This code generates invalid C code:\r\n```cython\r\n    cdef char* m = <char*> mem.PyMem_Malloc(20)\r\n    m[:4] = [1,2,3,4]\r\n```\r\nIt creates a Python list and then assigns a Python slice:\r\n```\r\n    if (__Pyx_PyObject_SetSlice(((PyObject *)__pyx_v_m), __pyx_t_1, 0, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 1, 1) < 0) __PYX_ERR(0, 16, __pyx_L4_error)\r\n```\r\nIt should generate the normal array slice assignment code instead. There's probably something wrong with the byte string coercion here, which might apply to some parts of the analysis but not others. It should not apply here at all.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "The same apparently applies to other types of `char*` slice assignment, which should also use copying code (and probably just call `memcpy()`).\r\n```c\r\n  /* \"crashtest4.pyx\":2\r\n * def crash(unsigned char *a, unsigned char *b, int len):\r\n *     a[:len] = b[:len]             # <<<<<<<<<<<<<<\r\n */\r\n  __pyx_t_1 = __Pyx_PyBytes_FromStringAndSize(((const char*)__pyx_v_b) + 0, __pyx_v_len - 0); if (unlikely(!__pyx_t_1)) __PYX_ERR(0, 2, __pyx_L1_error)\r\n  __Pyx_GOTREF(__pyx_t_1);\r\n  if (__Pyx_PyObject_SetSlice(((PyObject *)__pyx_v_a), __pyx_t_1, 0, __pyx_v_len, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 1, 1) < 0) __PYX_ERR(0, 2, __pyx_L1_error)\r\n  __Pyx_DECREF(__pyx_t_1); __pyx_t_1 = 0;\r\n```\r\n",
